;	and use stat(2) on the unique file to check if its link count has increased to  2.<br />&gt;	Do not use the return value of the link() call.<br />&gt;<br />&gt;Is this still the case??  What exactly is broken?<br /><br />This is still the case.<br /><br />O_CREAT | O_EXCL is fundamentally broken in NFSv2 - this is not a linux<br />issue, it's simply how NFS works. There's no way to work around it: NFS v2<br />is so stateless that you simply cannot do locking with a O_CREAT.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.rutgers.edu<br />Please read the FAQ at <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
